<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-831-147  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 831 147.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CAD-CAM International  Dec 1990 v9 n12 p11(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Surviving the slowdown. (UK CAD vendors weather the recession)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Clarke, Charles.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The worldwide Cadcam market is maturing: average growth rate indeveloped markets in 1989 was just 16.3 percent, according toDatapro, a market research firm.andP;  The situation in the UK is nodifferent: managers decide to invest or not invest in Cadcam onthe basis of return on investment (ROI), what the managers thinkthey will realize in increased drawing productivity, increaseddesign productivity, and cost reductions in design and production.andO;But reduced design cost is an ineffective measure since people arethe major part of design cost.andP;  Automating does not save designcost, but automating does enable engineers to produce betterdesigns, reduce efforts, and improve time to market.andP;  Vendorstrategies in a recession are to establish a defensible marketposition and to concentrate on 'state of the market' products.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     CAD/CAMMarketing StrategyMarket AnalysisHardware VendorsUnited KingdomSoftware PublishersFinancial Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>